  "prompt": "How do I take input from STDIN in Python?",
  "response": "In Python, you can take input from standard input (STDIN) using the built-in `input()` function. This function reads a line from the input, converts it to a string (stripping a trailing newline), and returns it.\n\nHere's a basic example:\n\n```python\n# Taking input from the user\nuser_input = input(\"Please enter something: \")\n\n# Output the input back to the user\nprint(\"You entered:\", user_input)\n```\n\nWhen you run this code, it will display a prompt asking the user to enter something. Once the user enters the input and presses Enter, it will store the input in the variable `user_input` and then print it.\n\n### Reading multiple values\nIf you want to read multiple values in a single line separated by spaces, you can use the `split()` method:\n\n```python\n# Taking multiple inputs in one line\nuser_input = input(\"Enter multiple values separated by spaces: \")\n\n# Splitting the input into a list\nvalues = user_input.split()\n\n# Output the list of values\nprint(\"You entered:\", values)\n```\n\n### Converting input types\nRemember that input from `input()` is always a string. If you need to convert it into an integer or another type, you'll need to do that explicitly:\n\n```python\n# Taking an integer input\nnumber = int(input(\"Please enter a number: \"))\nprint(\"You entered the number:\", number)\n```\n\n### Using `sys.stdin`\nFor more complex scenarios, you can also read directly from `sys.stdin` using the `sys` module, which is particularly useful for reading multiple lines or when you're dealing with input in a different context (like reading from a file or when redirected):\n\n```python\nimport sys\n\nprint(\"Enter multiple lines of text (Press Ctrl+D or Ctrl+Z to end):\")\n\n# Read all lines from standard input until EOF\ninput_lines = sys.stdin.read()\n\nprint(\"You entered:\")\nprint(input_lines)\n```\n\nThis will read all the text from standard input until EOF (End Of File) is reached.",
